column1: Welcome to the Smart Contract Builder basics
column2: Welcome to The Oracle Problem, or Your First dApp
column3: Welcome to The Need to Decentralize

column1: This tutorial is going to introduce you to the controls of the game
column2: This tutorial is going to take you through building the LinkPal contract
column3: This tutorial will explain Data misfires and what happens if a Contract uses bad data

column1: Messages like this are stored in the Message menu
column2: dApps or Decentralized Applications consist of one or more Smart Contracts
column3: Jane has $100 in PayPal and wants to buy $100 worth of ETH. Meanwhile Bob has ETH and is willing to trade with her

column1: Open the Message menu
column2: A Smart Contract is code that lives and executes on a blockchain
column3: Money in PayPal is not a cryptocurrency and on a blockchain therefore it cannot natively be traded for ETH

column1: Good job!
column2: The apps of today utilize data in systems. dApps are no different however there exists a problem
column3: To solve this, LinkPal requires that Bob opens an invoice on PayPal for $100 while also having $100 of ETH

column1: To build Decentralized Applications, 3 things will be needed: Data, Nodes and Contracts
column2: Smart Contracts cannot access the systems that regular apps can. This is known as The Oracle Problem
column3: When Jane sees that Bob has $100 of ETH, Jane will pay $100 to the Invoice, the Node will see and release the $100 ETH to Jane

column1: Select the Binance ETH/USD data source from the Data menu
column2: To solve this problem we must utilize blockchain middleware
column3: This means it is very important that the LinkPal Contract is able to know the price of ETH. If the wrong price of ETH was used Jane could end up receiving more or less than $100. That's not good!

column1: Good job! Items in placement can be rotated by pressing Q or E
column2: In Smart Contract Builder this is known as a Node
column3: The ETH/USD Data source is going to get a 100% corruption level meaning when it is called by a Contract it has a 100% chance of giving bad data

column1: Rotate the data now
column2: To get the LinkPal Contract online you will have to use 2 Nodes
column3: People don't like it when technology doesn't work, especially when it comes to their money

column1: Good job! Place the data source somewhere into the level
column2: Reminder, white Wires represent Off-Chain Data...
column3: To make sure the Contract gets a reliable price of ETH we can use Decentralization

column1: Good job! Items can be re-placed by selecting it and pressing R
column3: This means placing down multiple sources of ETH/USD data to call and average them out

column1: Go ahead and re-place the Data into a different cell
column2: Remember! Data has to pass through a Node first
column3: You've been given 3 sources of ETH/USD to place and the Node has been given two more Ports

column1: Wires are used to connect items to form systems
column2: Congratulations! You have built your first dApp
column3: You need at least 2/3 of the data to not Misfire for a successful Contract use

column1: A Node has been placed. Press the Wire button to place down a wire and then connect the Data to the Node
column2: Press OK to return to the Main Menu
column3: Press OK to return to the Main Menu

column1: A Price Feed Contract has been placed into the level
To build the Contract we will need to know the Data sources it requires
Select the Contract and then view the Data Required
Good job! We can see that this Contract requires an ETH/USD Data source
Luckily for us we have a Node connected to Binance's ETH/USD API
Lets go ahead and connect the Node to the Price Feed Contract now
Good job! This Contract is now online
This completes the Smart Contract Builder basics tutorial
Press OK to return to the Main Menu
